# Tripify Demo Flow Script

## Purpose

This document defines the recommended product demo flow for Tripify.

It is designed for presentations, walkthroughs, and product explanation.

---

# Demo Goal

Show that Tripify helps users:

- sign in easily
- create a trip
- plan a trip day by day
- invite friends into the trip
- end the trip
- rate the trip
- publish the trip as a reusable template
- clone a template into a new trip

---

# Demo Story

## Main Narrative

Tripify is a collaborative trip planning platform that helps users create organized travel plans, invite other people into those plans, and turn successful trips into reusable templates for future travel.

---

# Demo Flow Overview

1. Sign in with Google
2. View current user state
3. Create a new trip
4. Show auto-generated trip days
5. Add itinerary items
6. Invite another user
7. Show invitation handling
8. Show trip members
9. End the trip
10. Submit a rating
11. Publish trip as template
12. Browse templates
13. Clone template into a new trip

---

# Detailed Demo Script

## Step 1: Landing Page

### What to show
- branding
- travel-focused design
- value proposition
- sign in CTA

### What to say
Tripify is a collaborative travel planner designed for people who want to organize trips clearly, share plans with others, and reuse good trip plans as future templates.

---

## Step 2: Sign in with Google

### What to show
- login page or login button
- Google sign-in flow

### What to say
Users can log in using Google immediately without needing a separate email/password registration flow.

---

## Step 3: Authenticated State

### What to show
- current user info in navbar or profile area
- trip dashboard / my trips page

### What to say
Once signed in, the system syncs the user into the application and loads their trip workspace.

---

## Step 4: Create Trip

### What to show
- create trip form
- fields:
  - title
  - destination
  - date range
  - traveler count
  - budget
  - description

### Example demo data
- title: `Japan Spring Trip`
- destination: `Tokyo`
- date range: `2026-04-10` to `2026-04-14`
- traveler count: `2`
- budget: `45000`

### What to say
Users can define the trip at a high level first, then the system creates the structure they need to start planning.

---

## Step 5: Show Generated Trip Days

### What to show
- trip detail page
- day sections automatically created
- `Day 1` to `Day N`

### What to say
The app automatically generates trip days based on the selected travel range, so the user can immediately start planning by day.

---

## Step 6: Add Itinerary Items

### What to show
- add itinerary item to one or more days
- inputs:
  - title
  - place
  - time
  - estimated cost
  - note

### Example demo items
#### Day 1
- Visit Shibuya
- Dinner at local restaurant

#### Day 2
- Tokyo Disneyland

### What to say
Each day can contain structured itinerary items, making the trip easier to read, organize, and share with others.

---

## Step 7: Invite Another User

### What to show
- invitation UI
- invite by email or user
- send invitation action

### What to say
One of the core collaboration features is the ability to invite another user into the same trip so they can participate in planning and viewing the trip together.

---

## Step 8: Invitation Acceptance

### What to show
- switch to invited account if available
- invitations page
- accept invitation action

### What to say
The invited user receives the trip invitation and can explicitly accept or decline it.

### Then show
- return to trip detail
- members list now includes both users

### What to say
Once accepted, the invited person becomes part of the trip and appears in the trip members list.

---

## Step 9: Show Members

### What to show
- trip members panel
- owner + accepted member

### What to say
This makes the trip collaborative while still keeping ownership and trip structure clear.

---

## Step 10: End the Trip

### What to show
- end trip action
- choose completed or ended early
- status updates on trip

### What to say
At the end of the trip, the owner can close out the trip, which also unlocks post-trip actions such as rating.

---

## Step 11: Submit Rating

### What to show
- rating modal or form
- score 1–5
- optional comment
- submitted rating appears in ratings list

### Example demo rating
- score: `5`
- comment: `The plan was easy to follow and very useful.`

### What to say
After a trip has ended, participants can rate it. This creates a post-trip feedback loop and adds value to successful trip planning.

---

## Step 12: Publish as Template

### What to show
- publish template button
- published state visible on trip

### What to say
If a trip plan is successful, the owner can publish that trip as a reusable template.

---

## Step 13: Browse Templates

### What to show
- templates page
- list of published templates
- selected template card

### What to say
Published trips can be discovered and reused as starting points for future trips.

---

## Step 14: Clone Template

### What to show
- open template detail
- clone template form
- new title
- new date range
- create new trip from template

### What to say
Instead of planning every trip from scratch, users can reuse an existing template and create a new trip with its own dates and ownership.

---

## Step 15: Show New Cloned Trip

### What to show
- newly created trip detail page
- copied day structure
- copied itinerary items
- clean ownership for current user

### What to say
The cloned trip is now a separate independent trip based on the original template.

---

